---
import Base from '../../layouts/Base.astro';

const rubyCode = `scores = [85, 92, 78, 96, 61, 74]
passing = scores.select { |s| s >= 75 }
avg = passing.sum / passing.length
puts "Passing average: \#{avg}"`;
---
<Base title="Tyra vs Ruby" description="Comparing Tyra and Ruby for LLM code generation — training data vs spec injection">
  <style>
    .compare-header { margin-bottom: 2rem; }
    .compare-header p { color: var(--text-muted); max-width: 680px; }
    .rate-grid { display: grid; grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr; gap: 1.5rem; margin: 2rem 0; }
    @media (max-width: 600px) { .rate-grid { grid-template-columns: 1fr; } }
    .rate-card { background: var(--bg-secondary); border: 1px solid var(--border); border-radius: 10px; padding: 1.5rem; text-align: center; }
    .rate-card.tyra { border-color: var(--accent); }
    .rate-value { font-size: 2.5rem; font-weight: 700; }
    .rate-card.tyra .rate-value { color: var(--accent); }
    .rate-lang { font-size: 0.875rem; color: var(--text-muted); margin-top: 0.25rem; }
    .rate-note { font-size: 0.75rem; color: var(--text-muted); margin-top: 0.5rem; }
    .side-by-side { display: grid; grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr; gap: 1rem; margin: 1.5rem 0; }
    @media (max-width: 700px) { .side-by-side { grid-template-columns: 1fr; } }
    .code-block-label { font-size: 0.8rem; color: var(--text-muted); text-transform: uppercase; letter-spacing: 0.06em; font-weight: 600; margin-bottom: 0.4rem; }
    .tradeoff-list { color: var(--text-muted); padding-left: 1.5rem; font-size: 0.925rem; }
    .tradeoff-list li { margin-bottom: 0.5rem; line-height: 1.7; }
    .honest-note { background: var(--bg-secondary); border-left: 3px solid var(--border); padding: 0.75rem 1rem; border-radius: 0 6px 6px 0; color: var(--text-muted); font-size: 0.875rem; margin: 1.5rem 0; }
    .highlight-box { background: rgba(247, 129, 102, 0.07); border: 1px solid rgba(247, 129, 102, 0.3); border-radius: 8px; padding: 1rem 1.25rem; margin: 1.5rem 0; }
    .highlight-box p { color: var(--text); margin: 0; }
  </style>

  <div class="compare-header">
    <h1>Tyra vs Ruby</h1>
    <p>
      Ruby has the highest LLM pass rate in our benchmark at 99%. That reflects decades of
      training data — LLMs know Ruby extremely well. Tyra, with zero training data, achieves
      88.7% through spec injection. This comparison is about understanding what that gap means.
    </p>
  </div>

  <div class="rate-grid">
    <div class="rate-card">
      <div class="rate-value">99.0%</div>
      <div class="rate-lang">Ruby</div>
      <div class="rate-note">Single seed — enormous training data corpus</div>
    </div>
    <div class="rate-card tyra">
      <div class="rate-value">88.7%</div>
      <div class="rate-lang">Tyra + spec</div>
      <div class="rate-note">Multi-seed mean (3 seeds), zero training data</div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="highlight-box">
    <p>
      <strong>The key point:</strong> Ruby's 99% is built on 30+ years of public code, tutorials,
      Stack Overflow answers, and books. Tyra's 88.7% is built on a single spec document injected
      into the prompt. That 10 percentage point gap represents the cost of being a new language —
      and spec injection is how you close most of it on day one.
    </p>
  </div>

  <h2>Side-by-side: data transformation</h2>

  <div class="side-by-side">
    <div>
      <div class="code-block-label">Tyra</div>
      <pre><code>{`fn main() -> Unit
  let scores = [85, 92, 78, 96, 61, 74]
  let passing = list.filter(scores, fn(s) s >= 75 end)
  let total = list.fold(passing, 0, fn(acc, s) acc + s end)
  let avg = total / list.len(passing)
  println("Passing average: #{avg}")
end`}</code></pre>
    </div>
    <div>
      <div class="code-block-label">Ruby</div>
      <pre><code>{rubyCode}</code></pre>
    </div>
  </div>

  <p style="color: var(--text-muted);">
    Ruby's method-chaining style is elegant and concise. Tyra uses explicit module functions
    (<code>list.filter</code>, <code>list.fold</code>) rather than methods on the collection,
    which is more explicit about what's happening — a tradeoff that helps LLMs working only
    from a spec document.
  </p>

  <h2>Training data vs spec injection</h2>

  <p style="color: var(--text-muted);">
    The experiment Tyra runs is: <em>if you design a language specifically to be spec-injectable,
    how close can you get to a language with decades of training data?</em>
  </p>

  <p style="color: var(--text-muted);">
    The answer, at 88.7% vs 99%, is: close enough to be useful. For teams building
    internal tools or prototypes with LLM assistance, that gap is meaningful but not prohibitive —
    especially when Tyra's type system catches bug classes that Ruby's dynamic typing misses entirely.
  </p>

  <h2>Honest tradeoffs</h2>

  <ul class="tradeoff-list">
    <li><strong>Ruby wins:</strong> 99% pass rate, massive ecosystem (gems), Rails, Sinatra, decades of production use. Ruby is battle-tested.</li>
    <li><strong>Ruby wins:</strong> Dynamic typing enables rapid prototyping patterns that Tyra's static type system makes more verbose.</li>
    <li><strong>Ruby wins:</strong> Enormous community, learning resources, hiring pool.</li>
    <li><strong>Tyra advantage:</strong> Static types catch bugs at compile time that Ruby finds at runtime (or never, for rarely-executed paths).</li>
    <li><strong>Tyra advantage:</strong> <code>Float</code> has no <code>==</code>, preventing NaN bugs. Ruby inherits IEEE 754 semantics silently.</li>
    <li><strong>Tyra advantage:</strong> 88.7% first-try pass rate with zero training data shows the spec-injection approach works — the gap to Ruby will narrow as LLMs train on more Tyra code.</li>
    <li><strong>Tyra is new:</strong> No gems equivalent, small ecosystem, active compiler development. Ruby is the safer production choice today.</li>
  </ul>

  <div class="honest-note">
    Tyra is inspired by Ruby's readability and is not a replacement for it. Ruby's 99% benchmark
    result is something to aspire to, not compete with. The comparison shows that spec injection
    is a viable path for new languages to achieve high LLM accuracy without waiting for years
    of incidental training data.
  </div>

  <p style="color: var(--text-muted);">
    <a href="/leaderboard">View full leaderboard &rarr;</a>
  </p>
</Base>
